"reviewcomment":"At WW&amp;S, you will get:<br><br>-Absurdly cheap, quality wines (most recently: $5 Malbec, $7 Pinotage; $4 Carmenere, $5 Corbieres).<br>-Absurdly cheap low-end versions of snooty wines ($20 Brunello), cheaper than at the winery $16 Wiemer Riesling<br>-Interesting vineyards/distributors you might not find elsewhere<br>-Solicitous blue-collar staff, quirky register people<br>-Great prices on all other booze<br><br>At WW&amp;S, you will NOT get:<br><br>-Precious presentation<br>-Artisanal tastings<br>-Genteel European staff<br><br>As long as you know what it is, WW&amp;S will hit the mark every time. Sometimes it gets more crowded here than a 99-cent store in Times Square, so pushing a cart or even carrying a basket can get annoying fast, but you will put up with it to stock your fridge/wine rack/dorm room with 6 bottles of wine for $30.",
