"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/0s36n1OvRSP0h6wktnN93A/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Since the spouse read the NYT article a few months. ago this has become our go to bakery for croissants and baguettes. We live 30 miles away. The croissants are fresh flaky buttery and 2.00, a refreshing change from the stale 3.25 croissants you get elsewhere . The creme filled croissant is unique and lighter than it sounds. One of the nicer items  is a large roll suitable for pan bagnat. Actually I wish they made this Tunisian sandwich.If you&#39;re there to eat on the spot , pick up a baguette slathered with good butter, which seems to be the favorite of the taxi drivers in the area. If you have time enjoy your croissant at the sunny table in the front secure in the knowledge that you have had an experience more authentically French than in the high priced places a few blocks to the South.<br><br>Update 2.10.14 - confirmed they do indeed have a pan bagnat on the menu, my bad. Used to seeing these pre-made and on display in France - they are best that way so the oil soaks into the bread. New favorite is the ficelle with bacon and cheese. Pain au chocolat was great this weekend.",
