"ogimage":"http://s3-media4.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/lIcI7_SlTpVfX-nfnn_24w/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Lacryma Christi! Not a curse nor a lament, it&#39;s the name of my favorite red wine (literally means Tears of Christ), made from grapes growing on Mount Vesuvius in Pompeii. After my last trip to Naples, I was hooked and it wasn&#39;t so easy to find in NYC (I can&#39;t find it anywhere in New Orleans, sadly). Enter West Street Wine.<br><br>We go way back. When I worked at a bar nearby 5 years ago, this is where I&#39;d stop on the way to work to have my own provisions for the night (the bar I worked at had shitty wine) to share with my good friend, who was also the sound guy. We&#39;d drown our sorrows as we watched whatever shitty band or comedian I had booked on a Tuesday night, not unlike Christ crying over Lucifer&#39;s fall from heaven, lending divine fertility to the soil that would later be mixed with ash. Then we&#39;d drink another bottle as we walked home to Brooklyn, all the way from Downtown, through Chinatown and the LES and over the Williamsburg Bridge. Once there, we&#39;d be so sotted that one of us would climb to the top of the damn thing. Which one? Hint: not the one wearing platform boots. THOSE were the days.<br><br>I stopped in to West Street Wine most recently when staying with my friend who lived in the area, grabbed two or four bottles of Lacryma Christi and relived old memories. A reasonably priced red table wine, West Street charges a fair price, as I&#39;ve seen it sold for as much as $5 more a bottle elsewhere. <br><br>I also stopped in here on for my New Year&#39;s bottle of Nicolas Feuillatte, also at a good price. I figure they can charge more because it&#39;s pretty much the only liquor store in the area. And oh, they deliver, too.",
